\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 A document is composed of a sequence of \i systems\i0 .  A system is an indivisible group of staves spanning the width of the page.  The staves are grouped at their left-hand end with linkage bars and brackets (see \b Brackets\b0 ).  On the screen various non-printing markers are associated with a system to identify objects related to it.  Systems may include prefatory staves (also called incipits).  The following example illustrates a system with three 5-line staves:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_1.eps \width7140\height3080
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 At the left end there is an incipit for each staff using facsimile notation, followed by a bracket and a staff linkage bar, followed by the contents of each staff.  On the display screen, some non-printing markers are also shown at the right-and end of the system.  These markers are shown enlarged in this screenshot:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_2.eps \width6240\height3460
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 In the margin will be found the following markers:\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·  The \i system marker\i0 , a square marker at the corner of the system.  This marker is highlighted (as above) if this system is the selected system.  A system may be selected by clicking on its system marker. Various commands refer to the selected system.  Command-clicking or double-clicking on the system marker will raise the System Inspector.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	The \i staff number\i0 , an integer.  Staves are numbered starting with 1.  Staff numbers include hidden staves, but of course hidden staves are not displayed.  The following screenshot shows a part of a system in which staves 1,2 and 4 are hidden:\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_12.tiff \width3200\height2140
}¬}   \par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	\i Page format marker\i0 , in the column to the right of the system marker.  Page Formats specify the margins of the page (see \b Page Format\b0 ).  The first system of a document always has a page format, which will take effect until the next page format marker is encountered.  Although a document may have more than one page format, it is only in exceptional situations to do so.  It is useful to Command-click or double-click a page format marker, which will cause the Page Format Inspector to be shown.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	\i Running title markers\i0 , in the column to the right of the system marker.  There is one marker for each running title associated with the system (see \b Running Titles\b0 ). The shape of the marker indicates whether the running title is a page footer or page header.  A running title may be selected by clicking on its marker.  It is useful to Command-click or double-click a marker, which will cause the running title inspector to be shown.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	\i System keep marker\i0 , in the column to the right of the system marker.  If a system specifies page breaking in a way other than the default, a page-shaped marker is shown as in the following screenshot:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_3.tiff \width4160\height2160
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The purpose of this is so the user can quickly identify where exceptional page breaking has been specified.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Creating a System\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 There are several ways to make a system.  Normally the first system in the document is created automatically whenever a new document is created as specified by the New Document panel (see the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 ocument\f2\f2 ®\f1\f1 N\f1 ew...\f0  command).  Commands that may also create systems in various circumstances are in the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ystem\f0  menu:   \fs24\f1\b0\i0 N\f1 ew System\f0 , \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 pill Bar\f0 , and \fs24\f1\b0\i0 P\f1 aste Systems\f0 .  These are described in the reference section.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The System Inspector\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 With the System Inspector it is possible to alter the characteristics of a system and its staves.  The System Inspector is shown here:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_13.eps \width6660\height7060
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The Inspector is divided into two portions.  The upper portion displays one of several aspects relating to the system as a whole.  The lower portion displays one of several aspects relating to the staves.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\ql\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 When a system is selected, its attributes will be displayed by the inspector.  Any attribute can be changed, and the changes will take effect when the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0  button is pressed.  The staff buttons specify which staff is being inspected.  Multiple staves may be selected. In a  multiple staff selection, the inspector will display those attributes that are identical across the selection.  For non-identical attributes, the inspector will indicate a multiple selection in a way depending on what kind of control displays the attribute.  For example, a matrix of buttons shows no selection; a popup menu reads \fs24\f1\b0\i0 m\f1 ultiple selection\f0 , a text box is empty, and a switch shows a horizontal line.  If a control indicating a multiple selection is changed, the change will take effect on all selected staves when \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0  is pressed.  If \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0  is pressed, no action is taken for attributes which remain indicating a multiple selection.  Therefore, a multiple selection indication can be read as "ignore" when SET is pressed.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f0\b0\i0 T\f0 he\f1\f1  \f1 Number of staves\f0  field in the midle of the inspector panel shows the number of staves in the current system.  If there is no current system, then this will show 0 and be highlighted.  Typing an integer followed by Return (or pressing \fs24\f1\b0\i0 N\f1 ew System\f0 )  will create a system having the indicated number of staves.  This is the only context in which pressing Return will perform a  button press.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 System Aspects\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The following aspects can be selected using the popup menu at the top of the System Inspector:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Indentation\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Specifies the left and right indentation of the system, expressed in the measurement units specified on the \b Page Layout\b0  panel .\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_10.tiff \width3220\height1900
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 These indents are counted \i in addition to\i0  the margins in effect on the page.  Therefore, system indentations should be used only in exceptional circumstances (such as to allow space for the prefatory staves), and not as the usual means of setting the width of the system.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Numbering\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 This aspect permits the definition of page numbers and bar numbers.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_5.tiff \width3980\height2060
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The default is that bar numbers and page numbers begin with 1, and increment according to conventional musical rules.  However, this aspects overrides the default to allow page and bar numbers to restart at another value. \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 tart new page number\f0 : if the box is checked, a page number may be inserted to override the page number of the page on which this system appears when it is paginated.  If more than one system on a page has this option checked, then the page number used is that of the lowest system on the page.  \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 tart new bar number\f0 : if the box is checked, a bar number may be inserted to override the bar number of the first bar of the system.   This aspect also contains a textfield to permit raising or lowering the baseline on which bar numbers are printed. This takes effect only on the inspected system.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Keep\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Specifies whether the inspected system is to kept on the same page as the system following it.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_6.tiff \width3500\height1660
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 This allows the default pagination of the document to be overridden, and is to be used in exceptional circumstances only.  It is wise not to specify "keep" for a system that will be kept anyway as a result of the default pagination. \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Vertical Layout Options\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Overrides the default vertical layout (between staves) to permit the automatic allowance of more space between systems.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_7.tiff \width3580\height2080
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 E\f1 xpand enough for equal spacing\f0 :  specifies that the formatter should ensure that the origins of staves are separated by an equal amount of space.  This calculates an amount for expansion, and disables the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 E\f1 xpand to Amount\f0  field.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 E\f1 xpand to Amount\f0 :  specifies the amount of vertical expansion of the system.  100% is the default, and refers to the default separation between staves as computed by the formatter.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 E\f1 xtra Group Separation\f0 :  specifies the number of staff spacing units of extra separation between bracketted groups of staves in the system.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Adjustment Options\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 This is used to select which of two adjustment algorithms to use.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_8.tiff \width3500\height1780
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Normally, barlines coincide, so the first option is the default.  However, in some polymetric schemes, bars are of different metrical length, and are formatted not to coincide.  See the section on \b Polymetric Notation\b0  for details.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 System Styles\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 This is used for specifying system styles.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_9.tiff \width3760\height2460
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 See the separate chapter on  \b System Styles\b0  for details.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 System Separator\par
